=3D"&lt;p&gt;Fibonacci numbers form a recursive sequence where each number =
is the sum of the two preceding ones, starting with 0 and 1. This sequence =
can be mathematically expressed as F0 =3D 0, F1 =3D 1, and Fn =3D Fn-1 + Fn=
-2 for n &amp;gt; 1, generating a series that begins 0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 1=
3, 21, and so forth. Notably, as n increases, the ratio of consecutive Fibo=
nacci numbers approaches the golden ratio (approximately 1.618). The concep=
t was first introduced in 1202 in the book &amp;quot;Liber Abaci&amp;quot; =
by Leonardo of Pisa, also known as Fibonacci, who aimed to demonstrate the =
advantages of Arabic numerals over Roman numerals in calculations. &lt;/p&g=
t;
&lt;p&gt;One famous problem from this book involves rabbit populations, ill=
ustrating how Fibonacci numbers can model growth patterns. Additionally, ev=
ery positive integer can be expressed uniquely as a sum of nonadjacent Fibo=
nacci numbers, a principle known as Zeckendorf&amp;#039;s theorem. The Fibo=
nacci sequence also connects to the Lucas numbers, a sequence with similar =
recurrence relations. Interestingly, these numbers appear in biological con=
texts, such as the ancestry of honeybees, highlighting their relevance in n=
ature and mathematics.&lt;/p&gt;
