gray-900 mb-6 tracking-tight">Fibonacci Number</h1><div class=3D"mb-10"><di=
v><p class=3D"text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-600 font-sans font-light mb-6 l=
eading-relaxed">Fibonacci numbers form a recursive sequence where each numb=
er is the sum of the two preceding ones, starting with 0 and 1. This sequen=
ce can be mathematically expressed as F0 =3D 0, F1 =3D 1, and Fn =3D Fn-1 +=
 Fn-2 for n &gt; 1, generating a series that begins 0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13=
, 21, and so forth. Notably, as n increases, the ratio of consecutive Fibon=
acci numbers approaches the golden ratio (approximately 1.618). The concept=
 was first introduced in 1202 in the book "Liber Abaci" by Leonardo of Pisa=
, also known as Fibonacci, who aimed to demonstrate the advantages of Arabi=
c numerals over Roman numerals in calculations. </p>
<p class=3D"text-base text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-normal">One famous problem=
 from this book involves rabbit populations, illustrating how Fibonacci num=
bers can model growth patterns. Additionally, every positive integer can be=
 expressed uniquely as a sum of nonadjacent Fibonacci numbers, a principle =
known as Zeckendorf's theorem. The Fibonacci sequence also connects to the =
Lucas numbers, a sequence with similar recurrence relations. Interestingly,=
 these numbers appear in biological contexts, such as the ancestry of honey=
bees, highlighting their relevance in nature and mathematics.</p>
